  Sally, 75, began her career as a fresh-faced 18-year-old on the TV comedy Gidget between 1965 and 1966. The actress went on to star in The Flying Nun from 1967 to 1970, and then The Girl with Something Extra from 1973 to 1974. In 1976, Sally received critical acclaim for her performance in the television film Sybil, for which she received the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series or Movie. Her film career blossomed throughout the 1970s, which saw her starring in films including 1976’s Stay Hungry and 1977’s Smokey and the Bandit.  In the 1980s, Sally went on to win the Academy Award for Best Actress twice, for Norma Rae (1979) and Places in the Heart (1984). Her more memorable film performances from recent years include titles like 1989’s Steel Magnolias, 1993’s Mrs. Doubtfire and 1994’s Forrest Gump. In the 2000s, Sally has notably enjoyed a recurring role on the NBC medical drama ER, for which she won the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series in 2001. She also played Aunt May in The Amazing Spider-Man (2012) and returned for its sequel in 2014 - the same year she was presented with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.  